<font color="#FF0000">LESSONS LEARNED</font><br>
<tt>Fri Jul 11 18:31:03 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
My need to know these things and to develop research resources stems from my wanting to make sense out of my time incountry. What I mean by this is that probably because of my role as a medic and also because of my rank (or lack thereof), my perspective of the war and that of my unit engaged in is very narrow. It extends no farther than the company, but most times not beyond the platoon. I have never had a view of the larger picture, beyond the battles, the firefights, etc. that we engaged in. I have recently found a company commander of mine who was able to give me a larger picture on a couple of ops we were in, but this was after we were moved down to III Corps and at the end of my time there.<br><br>
I know you are trying your best at being as factual as possible. It is great that you have your compatriots to compare events with. But, I believe that what it would boil down to, other than the stats such as names, dates, WIA's, KIA's, is each of our own perception of events taken place.<br><br>
And there is absolutely nothing wrong with that.<br><br>
Give me a buzz when your book is published. I look foward to reading it. And, thanks for the info!
